            <scriptDesc>
              <summary>
                <p>The script of this Qurʾān manuscript is close to the early <hi rend="italic">kūfī</hi> script style B.Ia or <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>IV<hi rend="italic"> </hi>(according to the typologiy of <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">François Déroche</ref>). The shaft of <hi rend="italic">ʾalif </hi>and other vertical upstrokes slant to the right, that is a characteristic of B.Ia and <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>scripts. The letter <hi rend="italic">ǧīm </hi>in the initial position is closer to the B.I group. When in the middle of a word, the letter shaped like a bar that crosses the base line. This form is found in <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>IV as well as in the B.Ia group. The final form of the letter has a horizontal tail that end in a small hook, as in <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>IV<hi rend="italic"> </hi>and<hi rend="italic"> </hi>B.I manuscripts. The upper stroke of the letter <hi rend="italic">ṭāʾ </hi>slopes to the right as in<hi rend="italic"> ḥiǧāzī </hi>and B.Ia. The letter <hi rend="italic">ʿayn </hi>when isolated has the same tail with a small hook as the letter <hi rend="italic">ǧīm</hi>. Q<hi rend="italic">āf </hi>in the final position or isolated is more elongated vertically than in B.I manuscripts. The letter is vertical and does not slant to right as in <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī</hi>. The letter <hi rend="italic">nūn </hi>is more similar to <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>IV with its vertical body with a short return. The initial and medial <hi rend="italic">hāʾ </hi>rests on the base line and does not extend below it. This characteristic is closer to the <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>group. The letter <hi rend="italic">m</hi><hi rend="italic">īm </hi>in the middle and at the end of a word also rests on the base line, as in <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>scripts or <hi rend="italic">kūfī </hi>A.I script style. The script of the fragment could be considered as a transitional stage between the <hi rend="italic">ḥiǧāzī </hi>and early <hi rend="italic">kūfī </hi>scripts.</p>
                <p>The diacritical marks are in the shape of small dashes. No trace of vocalisation (red dots) can be observed, which could be another indication for the early dating of the fragment. Small strokes placed at the end of a line serve as line fillers. </p>
              </summary>
